This article is about an executive order issued by President Barack Obama in 2011, titled "Instituting a National Action Plan on Women, Peace, and Security." The order recognizes the importance of promoting women's participation in conflict prevention, management, and resolution, as well as in post-conflict relief and recovery. It also acknowledges the responsibility of all nations to protect their populations from genocide, war crimes, ethnic cleansing, and crimes against humanity, including sexual violence. The executive order establishes a National Action Plan on Women, Peace, and Security, which outlines activities and initiatives in areas such as national integration and institutionalization, participation in peace processes and decision-making, protection from violence, conflict prevention, and access to relief and recovery. The order assigns responsibilities to various executive departments and agencies, and establishes an interagency process for coordinating the implementation of the National Action Plan. The order also includes general provisions regarding its implementation, compliance, and legal implications.